        <para id="id1166007196409">One can determine T<sub>2</sub> by spin-echo measurements for a series of samples of known S/V values and prepare a calibration chart as shown in  <link target-id="id1165982453834"/>, with the intercept as <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontsize="12pt"><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:msub><m:mi>T</m:mi><m:mstyle fontsize="8pt"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2,</m:mn><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>bulk</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:msub></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ {  {1}  over  {T rSub { size 8{2, ital "bulk"} } } } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and the slope as 
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontsize="12pt"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>ρ</m:mi><m:mstyle fontsize="8pt"><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ρ rSub { size 8{2} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, one can thus find the specific surface area of an unknown sample of the same material.</para>
   
